In [26]:
# monthly trends
index_month = jobs.index.month
jobs_by_month = jobs.groupby(index_month).mean()

# plot


ax = jobs_by_month.plot(fontsize=6,linewidth=1)

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(18.5, 10.5)

ax.set_xlabel('Month',fontsize=10)
ax.set_ylabel('Mean unemployement rate', fontsize=10)
ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(0.8,0.8), fontsize=10)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.show()

In [40]:
jobs_decomp = {}

jobs_names = jobs.columns

for ts in jobs_names:
    ts_decomposition = seasonal_decompose(jobs[ts])
    jobs_decomp[ts] = ts_decomposition
In [45]:
jobs_seasonal = {}

for ts in jobs_names:
    jobs_seasonal[ts] = jobs_decomp[ts].seasonal`

In [156]:
seasonality_norm = (seasonality_df - seasonality_df .mean()) / (seasonality_df .max() - seasonality_df .min())
In [157]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

model = KMeans(n_clusters = 5)
model.fit(seasonality_norm.T)

labels = model.predict(seasonality_norm.T)
labels[:5]

len(labels)
Out[157]:
16
In [158]:
